{
  "text": "It is also worth noting that the refundL does not depend on the cost of capital (while the existence itself of the separating equilibrium does), because we assume that credit derivatives are private contracts. Since a bank can hedge the refundL without the counterpart being informed, the cost of capital does not enter the self selection constraint of the low type. On the contrary, it is easy to show that the penalty will depend on the cost of capital and is decreasing in this parameter if we assume that (i) the protection buyer could credibly commit ex-ante to retain the equity tranche risk and that, ex-post, this is incentive compatible or (ii) credit derivatives are public contracts. [CITATION_1] Even the high-type bank is not over-insuring its portfolio using CDS basket because anyone buying that insurance is assumed to be a low-type bank.",
